    <stitle>ELECTRICAL SYSTEM TROUBLESHOOTING GUIDE - 9800 - SHIFT CONTROL LINKAGE ADJUSTMENT PROCEDURE WITH MANUAL
        TRANSMISSION
    </stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcsection id="s13001" svcsectype="prodspec" division="truck" formnum="CTS-5094" date="03/31/1996">
        <title>SHIFT CONTROL LINKAGE ADJUSTMENT PROCEDURE WITH MANUAL TRANSMISSION</title>
        <apply>
            <configure>
                <truckmodelgroup/>

                <truckmodel>9600</truckmodel>
                <truckmodel>9700</truckmodel>
            </configure>
        </apply>
        <description>
            <geninfo>
                <lev1>
                    <para>The transmission shift control linkage used on the 9600 and 9700 vehicles is illustrated in
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1300101">Figure 1</hotlnk>. The shift control system consists of the following:
                    </para>
                    <seqlist style="arabic">
                        <item>
                            <para>The shift lever and its mounting parts located in the cab (
                                <hotlnk xrefid="f1300102">Figure 2</hotlnk>).
                            </para>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <para>The remote control tower assembly located on the top of the transmission (
                                <hotlnk xrefid="f1300103">Figure 3</hotlnk>).
                            </para>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <para>The control rod assembly which connects the shift lever (in the cab) to the
                                transmission remote control tower. Components of the control rod assembly are shown in
                                <hotlnk xrefid="f1300104">Figure 4</hotlnk>.
                            </para>
                        </item>
                    </seqlist>
                    <figure id="f1300101" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g1300101" filename="../figg13/G1300101.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                        <caption>Figure 1. Exploded View of the Shift Control Linkage</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1. TRANSMISSION CONTROL HOUSING</callout1>
                            <callout1>2. SHIFT LEVER SEAL</callout1>
                            <callout1>3. GEAR SHIFT KNOB</callout1>
                            <callout1>4. GEAR SHIFT LEVER</callout1>
                            <callout1>5. LEVER SEAL RETAINER</callout1>
                            <callout1>6. TRANSMISSION CONTROL SHIFT PATTERN</callout1>
                            <callout1>7. COTTER PIN</callout1>
                            <callout1>8. SPRING</callout1>
                            <callout1>9. SHIFT LEVER BOLT</callout1>
                            <callout1>10. REMOTE CONTROL HOUSING</callout1>
                            <callout1>11. PIVOT ROD</callout1>
                            <callout1>12. REMOTE CONTROL OUTER SHIFT LEVER</callout1>
                            <callout1>13. SELECTION LEVER</callout1>
                            <callout1>14. UPPER AND LOWER SHIFT ROD CLAMPS</callout1>
                            <callout1>15. TRANSMISSION CONTROL ROD</callout1>
                            <callout1>16. CONTROL ROD BALL</callout1>
                            <callout1>17. BELL</callout1>
                            <callout1>18. CONTROL ROD GUIDE</callout1>
                            <callout1>19. SELF-ALIGNING BEARING</callout1>
                            <callout1>20. SEAL RETAINER</callout1>
                            <callout1>21. BEARING SEAL</callout1>
                            <callout1>22. HEX HEAD BOLT</callout1>
                            <callout1>23. CLAMP</callout1>
                            <callout1>24. NYLON SHIFT LEVER PLUNGER</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="f1300102" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g1300102" filename="../figg13/G1300102.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                        <caption>Figure 2. Transmission Shift Lever in Cab</caption>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="f1300103" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g1300103" filename="../figg13/G1300103.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                        <caption>Figure 3. Remote Control Tower</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1. CONTROL ROD ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                            <callout1>2. OUTER SHIFT LEVER</callout1>
                            <callout1>3. PIVOT ROD ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                            <callout1>4. REMOTE CONTROL TOWER</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="f1300104" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g1300104" filename="../figg13/G1300104.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                        <caption>Figure 4. Components of the Control Rod Assembly</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1. CONTROL ROD BALL</callout1>
                            <callout1>2. CONTROL ROD</callout1>
                            <callout1>3. CLAMP BOLT</callout1>
                            <callout1>4. SELECTION LEVER</callout1>
                            <callout1>5. CLAMP BAR (2)</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <para>Control rod assemblies are provided in different lengths to accommodate various
                        engine/transmission combinations. The effective lengths (Dimension A,
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1300105">Figure 5</hotlnk>) for various combinations are listed in
                        <hotlnk document="s13001_7.xml" xrefid="hl1300101">SPECIFICATIONS</hotlnk>.
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f1300105" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g1300105" filename="../figg13/G1300105.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                        <caption>Figure 5. Control Rod Length</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>A. APPROXIMATE TRUE LENGTH</callout1>
                            <callout1>1. TRANSMISSION CONTROL ROD</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <para>With the cab lowered in driving position, the front (upper) end of the control rod connects to
                        the shift lever (in the cab) as shown in
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1300106">Figure 6</hotlnk>. The front end of the control rod is supported by
                        the control rod bearing (Item 6,
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1300106">Figure 6</hotlnk>) and the control rod ball is engaged into the shift
                        lever socket (Item 1).
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f1300106" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g1300106" filename="../figg13/G1300106.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                        <caption>Figure 6. Control Rod Front Connections</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1. SHIFT LEVER SOCKET</callout1>
                            <callout1>2. SPRING</callout1>
                            <callout1>3. CONTROL ROD</callout1>
                            <callout1>4. SUPPORT BRACKET</callout1>
                            <callout1>5. ROD GUIDE</callout1>
                            <callout1>6. BEARING</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <para>When the cab is raised (tilted), the shift lever socket disengages from the control ball and
                        the control rod bearing (connected to the shift lever housing) disengages from the control rod.
                        The control rod support bracket (Item 4,
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1300106">Figure 6</hotlnk>) keeps the control rod from falling out of position.
                    </para>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <para>When the cab is lowered, the control rod guide (Item 5,
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1300106">Figure 6</hotlnk>) guides the end of the control into alignment with
                        the control rod bearing. The spring (Item 2,
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1300106">Figure 6</hotlnk>) holds the shift lever in position to permit the
                        shift lever socket to engage with the control rod ball.
                    </para>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <para>The rear (lower) end of the control rod is connected to the transmission remote control tower
                        as shown in
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1300107">Figure 7</hotlnk>. The selection lever (Item 4,
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1300107">Figure 7</hotlnk>) which is the rear portion of the control rod
                        assembly is connected to the remote control outer shift lever (Item 5,
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1300107">Figure 7</hotlnk>) and to the lower end of the pivot rod assembly
                        (Item 3,
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1300107">Figure 7</hotlnk>). Swivel bearings are used at these locations to
                        provide flexibility and ease of operation.
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f1300107" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g1300107" filename="../figg13/G1300107.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                        <caption>Figure 7. Control Rod to Remote Control Tower Connections</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>A. 90 DEGREES</callout1>
                            <callout1>1. CONTROL ROD ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                            <callout1>2. REMOTE CONTROL TOWER</callout1>
                            <callout1>3. PIVOT ROD ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                            <callout1>4. SELECTION LEVER</callout1>
                            <callout1>5. OUTER SHIFT LEVER</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <para>The length of the pivot rod is adjustable to accommodate various engine/transmission
                        combinations. The effective lengths for various combinations are listed in
                        <hotlnk document="s13001_7.xml" xrefid="hl1300101">SPECIFICATIONS</hotlnk>
                        .
                    </para>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <para>If replacement of the pivot rod is required, refer to the parts catalog for the correct
                        replacement parts. Assemble the parts to provide the specified length (
                        <hotlnk document="s13001_7.xml" xrefid="hl1300101">SPECIFICATIONS</hotlnk>,
                        <hotlnk document="s13001_9.xml" xrefid="f1300121">Figure 21</hotlnk>or
                        <hotlnk document="s13001_10.xml" xrefid="f1300122">Figure 22</hotlnk>, Dimension "F") for the
                        engine and transmission used in the vehicle being serviced.
                    </para>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <para>Fuller and Spicer units have the pivot rod assembly attached directly to the remote control
                        tower rather than to a pivot rod bracket (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1300108">Figure 8</hotlnk>and
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1300109">Figure 9</hotlnk>).
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f1300108" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g1300108" filename="../figg13/G1300108.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                        <caption>Figure 8. Remote Control Tower for International Code 13MAB, 13MAC, 13MAW, 13MAX
                            and13MAY 9-Speed Transmissions and Spicer 13DAT, 13 DAU and 13DAW 10-Speed Transmissions
                        </caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1. REMOTE CONTROL TOWER</callout1>
                            <callout1>2. TURNBUCKLE</callout1>
                            <callout1>3. LOCK NUTS</callout1>
                            <callout1>4. PIVOT ROD ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="f1300109" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g1300109" filename="../figg13/G1300109.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                        <caption>Figure 9. Pivot Rod Mounting</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1. PIVOT ROD ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                            <callout1>2. REMOTE CONTROL OUTER SHIFT LEVER</callout1>
                            <callout1>3. REMOTE CONTROL TOWER</callout1>
                            <callout1>4. PIVOT ROD CONNECTION</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                </lev1>
            </geninfo>
        </description>
